WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.820
Hey everyone, my name is Cecil from the PositSupport team and I'm here with Jay, who's a colleague

00:00:12.820 --> 00:00:18.920
also on the PositSupport team, and we're going to walk through the Trusted Certificate Store

00:00:18.920 --> 00:00:21.200
on your server.

00:00:21.200 --> 00:00:27.760
So the Trusted Certificate Store is a list of all the pre-trusted SSL certificates that

00:00:27.760 --> 00:00:35.520
are trusted by your Linux distribution, and having your SSL certificate chain within this

00:00:35.520 --> 00:00:40.799
store is important so that you don't run into any SSL trust issues.

00:00:40.799 --> 00:00:46.080
So in our case, we're using Ubuntu 24.

00:00:46.080 --> 00:00:54.240
If you're using Red Hat or any other Linux Ubuntu distribution that isn't Ubuntu 24,

00:00:54.240 --> 00:00:57.599
the directories may be slightly different.

00:00:57.599 --> 00:01:03.840
It's all mentioned in our support article, but for today's demo with Ubuntu 24, this

00:01:03.840 --> 00:01:07.000
is in the user local share directory.

00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:15.879
So what we want to do is copy our SSL certificate only to the user local share directory.

00:01:15.879 --> 00:01:19.879
You can paste that there.

00:01:19.879 --> 00:01:25.839
Once copied across, we can run the update CA certificates command.

00:01:25.839 --> 00:01:33.959
So depending on if you already have your SSL certificate in the Trusted Store or not, in

00:01:33.959 --> 00:01:38.559
our case, we've already had this added, so you'll see zero added, but if you're adding

00:01:38.559 --> 00:01:44.760
your certificate for the first time to the Trusted Store, then you'll see one added,

00:01:44.760 --> 00:01:49.519
potentially more, depending on how your SSL certificates are managed.

00:01:49.519 --> 00:01:55.760
Now that we've done that, that should resolve any of the SSL trust issues that we see.

